piece Butterfly. Andrew Chan looks beyond Carey’s glamorous persona to explore her experience as a mixed-race woman in show business, her adventurous forays into house music and gospel, and her appeal to multiple generations of queer audiences. He also reckons with the transcendent ideal of the voice that Carey represents, showing how this international icon taught artists around the world to sing with soul-shaking intensity and a spirit of innovation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aMusic and racezUnited StatesxHistory. 0aPopular musiczUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 0aWomen lyricistszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aWomen singerszUnited StatesvBiography. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh  aBlack music, pop music, 1990s, 2000s, Music Box, The Emancipation of Mimi, ballad, nostalgia, pop music diva, Voice studies, whistle tone, Lambs, Queen of Christmas, fantasy, biracial, voice, tommy mottola.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Cultural and Area Studies 2023 Englishz978311131909408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Cultural and Area Studies 2023z978311131812708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079782440uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/32507040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477325087423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477325087/original  a978-3-11-079782-4  University of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a978-3-11-131812-7  EBOOK PACKAGE Cultural and Area Studies 2023b2023  a978-3-11-131909-4  EBOOK PACKAGE Cultural and Area Studies 